    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none mt-16 pt-12 border-t border-hairline">
      <h2 class="font-sans text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-ink mb-6">
        Allowed to Keep Terms (ATKT) & Academic Progression Guide
      </h2>
      
      <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mb-6">
        In the Indian higher education system—particularly within universities in Maharashtra, Gujarat, and Karnataka—the term <strong>ATKT (Allowed to Keep Terms)</strong> is one of the most significant academic concepts students encounter. It is a progression mechanism designed to prevent minor academic setbacks from halting a student’s education. Instead of forcing a student to repeat an entire year due to failing one or two subjects, the ATKT system allows them to proceed to the next semester or year, provided they fulfill specific eligibility thresholds.
      </p>

      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-8">
        <div class="rounded-sm border border-hairline p-5 bg-canvas-soft">
          <h3 class="font-sans text-base font-semibold text-ink mb-2">What is a Head of Passing?</h3>
          <p class="text-xs text-body leading-relaxed">
            A "head of passing" is any individual assessment component that you must pass independently. For example, in many technical courses, the <strong>Theory Exam (ESE)</strong> and the <strong>Internal Assessment (IA)</strong> are separate heads. Failing either one will mark you as failed in that head, even if your combined score is high.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-sm border border-hairline p-5 bg-canvas-soft">
          <h3 class="font-sans text-base font-semibold text-ink mb-2">What is a Year Drop (Detention)?</h3>
          <p class="text-xs text-body leading-relaxed">
            A Year Drop (also known as a Year Down or Detention) occurs when you do not meet the minimum credit or subject requirements to enter the next academic year. During a drop year, you are not allowed to attend classes or appear for the higher semester exams; you must focus solely on clearing your pending backlogs.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3 class="font-sans text-lg font-bold text-ink mt-8 mb-4">Mumbai University Engineering ATKT Rules (C-Scheme)</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Engineering degrees under Mumbai University (specifically under the C-Scheme syllabus regulation) follow a strict <strong>Heads of Passing</strong> counting system. Unlike general degrees where subjects are evaluated as a whole, engineering partitions every subject into multiple heads, such as Theory (End Sem), Term Work, Practicals, and Oral/Viva.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mb-4">
        To understand whether you qualify for promotion under Mumbai University Engineering, the following rules apply:
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-5 text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mb-6 space-y-2">
        <li><strong>First Year to Second Year (Sem 3 entry):</strong> You can have a maximum of <strong>8 outstanding failed heads of passing</strong> from Semesters 1 and 2 combined. Crucially, out of these 8 backlogs, no more than <strong>5 failed heads</strong> can be in the End Semester Examinations (Theory Papers).</li>
        <li><strong>Second Year to Third Year (Sem 5 entry):</strong> You must have <strong>completely cleared all subjects</strong> from the First Year (Semesters 1 and 2). This means you cannot enter the Third Year carrying even a single First-Year backlog. Additionally, you must not carry more than 8 failed heads from Semesters 3 and 4 combined (with a maximum of 5 in ESE).</li>
        <li><strong>Third Year to Fourth Year (Sem 7 entry):</strong> You must have <strong>completely cleared all subjects</strong> from both the First Year and the Second Year (Semesters 1, 2, 3, and 4). Furthermore, you cannot carry more than 8 failed heads from Semesters 5 and 6 combined (max 5 in ESE).</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="my-6 rounded-sm border border-warning/30 bg-warning-soft/10 p-4 text-xs text-warning-deep leading-relaxed">
        <strong>Warning:</strong> Outstanding backlogs from earlier years trigger an automatic Year Drop under the Year-Clearance rules. For example, if you enter Semester 5 with a single backlog remaining from Semester 1, you will face an immediate Year Down, even if your Semester 3 and 4 results are 100% clear.
      </div>

      <h3 class="font-sans text-lg font-bold text-ink mt-8 mb-4">Mumbai University B.Sc, B.Com, & B.A Rules (General CBCS)</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mb-4">
        For general undergraduate degree programs (B.Sc., B.Com., and B.A.) following the Choice Based Credit System (CBCS), the promotion rules are subject-oriented rather than head-oriented. The limits are calculated semester-wise to ensure students stay on track.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mb-4">
        The progression structure for general degrees includes:
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-5 text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mb-6 space-y-2">
        <li><strong>Moving to Year 2:</strong> A student is eligible for Semester 3 admission if he/she passes Semester 1 and Semester 2 completely, OR fails in <strong>no more than 2 subjects</strong> in Semester 1 AND <strong>no more than 2 subjects</strong> in Semester 2. Failing 3 subjects in a single semester will result in detention, even if the other semester is fully cleared.</li>
        <li><strong>Moving to Year 3:</strong> The student must have <strong>passed Semester 1 and Semester 2 completely</strong>. In addition, the student must pass Semester 3 and Semester 4 completely, OR fail in <strong>no more than 2 subjects</strong> in Semester 3 AND <strong>no more than 2 subjects</strong> in Semester 4.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="font-sans text-lg font-bold text-ink mt-8 mb-4">NEP 2020 Credit-Based Promotion System</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mb-4">
        With the implementation of the National Education Policy (NEP 2020), universities are transitioning toward a credit-accumulation system. Under this system, eligibility is no longer determined by counting failed subjects. Instead, promotion is based on earning a minimum number of cumulative credits.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mb-4">
        This is a much more flexible approach. For a standard 4-year engineering degree totaling 170–180 credits (averaging 44 credits per year):
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-5 text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mb-6 space-y-2">
        <li><strong>To Enter Second Year (Sem 3):</strong> A student must earn at least <strong>32 cumulative credits</strong> (out of 44).</li>
        <li><strong>To Enter Third Year (Sem 5):</strong> A student must accumulate at least <strong>76 cumulative credits</strong> (out of 88) across all prior semesters.</li>
        <li><strong>To Enter Fourth Year (Sem 7):</strong> A student must accumulate at least <strong>120 cumulative credits</strong> (out of 132) across all prior semesters.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mb-6">
        This credit-accumulation model means a student who fails multiple low-credit labs might still be promoted, whereas failing several high-credit core theory subjects will trigger a credit shortage and result in detention.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-sans text-lg font-bold text-ink mt-8 mb-4">Condonation & Grace Marks Ordinances</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mb-4">
        To prevent students from losing a year over 1 or 2 marks, Mumbai University incorporates specific condonation and grace marks ordinances. These are applied automatically during the result processing:
      </p>
      <ul class="list-style-none pl-0 text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mb-6 space-y-3">
        <li><strong>Ordinance 5042 (Passing Grace Marks):</strong> Allows up to 1% of the total aggregate marks (max 10 marks) to be added to a subject if the student is failing. For example, if you score 30/80 in engineering theory where passing is 32, the university can award 2 grace marks to help you clear.</li>
        <li><strong>Ordinance 5045 (Condonation):</strong> Deficiencies in passing heads can be condoned up to a total of 10 marks, which can be divided across a maximum of two subjects.</li>
        <li><strong>Ordinance 5046 (Extra-Curricular Marks):</strong> If you participate in NSS, NCC, Sports, or Cultural activities at the university level, you can receive 10 grace marks added to your grand total. These marks can also be used to pass a subject in case you are failing.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="font-sans text-lg font-bold text-ink mt-8 mb-4">Action Plan: What to Do If You Face a Year Drop</h3>
      <p class="text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Getting detained or receiving a Year Down is emotionally challenging, but it is not the end of your academic journey. Use the drop year constructively with this action plan:
      </p>
      <ol class="list-decimal pl-5 text-sm text-body leading-relaxed mb-6 space-y-2">
        <li><strong>Apply for Revaluation Immediately:</strong> If you failed a theory exam by 1 to 5 marks, apply for photocopy and revaluation. Scores frequently change during revaluation, and passing even one subject can pull you out of a Year Drop.</li>
        <li><strong>Identify the Bottlenecks:</strong> Analyze which subjects caused the failure. Is it a core mathematical paper like Applied Mathematics, or a practical head? Create a structured study schedule.</li>
        <li><strong>Attempt Golden KT/Supplementary Exams:</strong> Mumbai University conducts ATKT exams twice a year. Use the Winter and Summer cycles strategically. Do not attempt all 5 or 6 backlog papers at once if you are underprepared; focus on clearing the papers from the earliest semesters first to satisfy the Year-Clearance rule.</li>
        <li><strong>Utilize the Time Productively:</strong> Gain a skill, work on open-source projects, learn web development, or take up a remote internship. Having a productive gap year will make a great talking point during final placements.</li>
      </ol>
    </article>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

